{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17660060","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17660060"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:20:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:20:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22705"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22705","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22705"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15652"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111650"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15652"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22705"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93718"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"12922"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"45403"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45404"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111650","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111650"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents with a two-week history of painless jaundice and recent weight loss. Blood tests show an obstructive pattern of liver function tests. An abdominal computed tomography scan demonstrates a mass in the head of the pancreas causing biliary obstruction (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBased on this presentation, several physical signs could be considered.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following physical signs is most likely to be found?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A palpable epigastric mass","Tenderness in the epigastrium","Shifting dullness","A palpable, distended gallbladder","An enlarged left supraclavicular lymph node"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely sign is \u003Cstrong\u003Ea palpable, distended gallbladder\u003C/strong\u003E in the setting of painless obstructive jaundice due to a mass in the pancreatic head. Obstruction of the common bile duct proximal to the ampulla leads to gallbladder distension, making it more readily palpable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe finding of a palpable, distended gallbladder is is known as Courvoisier\u0027s sign. Courvoisier\u0027s law describes the significance of this sign - \u0027if, in the presence of jaundice, the (enlarged) gallbladder can be palpated, then the underlying cause is unlikely to be gallstones.\u0027 This points to a more sinister, malignant, aetiology. The gallbladder related to gallstone-induced inflammation is usually small, shrunken and not palpable. Courvoisier\u0027s sign is being described less and less - obesity covers everything...\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA palpable epigastric mass\u003C/strong\u003E is uncommon in pancreatic cancer at presentation because the pancreas lies retroperitoneally and early tumours, even if significant radiologically, are often not palpable on examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETenderness in the epigastrium\u003C/strong\u003E is more suggestive of inflammatory conditions such as pancreatitis or peptic disease; pancreatic cancer with obstructive jaundice typically presents without abdominal tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShifting dullness\u003C/strong\u003E indicates clinically detectable ascites, which is not a typical early feature of pancreatic head cancer and would suggest advanced peritoneal involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAn enlarged left supraclavicular lymph node\u003C/strong\u003E may occur with intra-abdominal malignancy but is an infrequent finding in pancreatic cancer and is less likely than a palpable distended gallbladder in this context.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Painless obstructive jaundice from a mass in the pancreatic head commonly presents with a distended, palpable gallbladder.","A palpable, non-tender gallbladder in jaundice suggests malignant obstruction rather than gallstones.","Ascites, epigastric tenderness, and palpable epigastric masses are less likely early features of pancreatic head malignancy."],"references":["Stoop TF, Javed AA, Oba A, et al. Pancreatic cancer. Lancet 2025; 405: 1182\u2013202. Available from: https://www.thelancet.com/pdfs/journals/lancet/PIIS0140-6736(25)00261-2.pdf","Gaillard F, Yap J, Knipe H, et al. Pancreatic neoplasms. Reference article, Radiopaedia.org (Accessed on 17 Aug 2025) https://doi.org/10.53347/rID-1832"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93718"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22705"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22044"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22044","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22044"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/pE3y0RAtDBDQfRZhZuP3QcJOb2Mz0b.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/pE3y0RAtDBDQfRZhZuP3QcJOb2Mz0b.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":570,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93718","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93718"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-17T21:19:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-17T21:20:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15652"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111650"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5"